#Text=Choose a Name for a Pet
#Text=It is estimated that 35-47 % of American households own dogs , and 30-37 % own cats .
#Text=These numbers do not even include other household pets !
#Text=Owning a pet is one thing , but it is another thing to think of a unique name .
#Text=If you are planning on bringing home a new member of the family , you may be wondering how to choose the perfect name .
#Text=Steps
#Text=Picking a Name Based On Your Pet
#Text=Evaluate pet appearance .
#Text=What your pet looks like may a good place to start when you want to name your new pet .
#Text=Consider things like :
#Text=Fur color or length .
#Text=( For example , if you own a long-hair dog or cat , you can name it " Shaggy " . )
#Text=Distinguishing colored patches .
#Text=( For example , you may name your pet " Boots " if it has color patches on his/her paws . )
#Text=Distinguishing features or injuries
#Text=Eye color ( For example , you may name your pet " Frankie " after Frank Sinatra , whose nickname was " Ol ' Blue Eyes . " )
#Text=Ear or head shape ( If your pet 's head is triangular , it might appear fox-like .
#Text=" Fox " or " Foxy " might be a good name for your pet . ) .
#Text=Identify pet personality .
#Text=How your pet acts may be another great way to pick the perfect name .
#Text=Observe your pet to distinguish unique characteristics
#Text=Unique vocalizations ( bark , meow , squeak , etc ) .
#Text=( For example , if your cat has a quiet meow , you may name it " Silence " )
#Text=Temperament such as happiness or sleepiness .
#Text=( " Happy , " " Sleepy , " " Peaceful , " " Bossy , " or " Cranky " might be good names . )
#Text=Consider your pet ’s uniqueness .
#Text=Some of the best names can come from the pet ’s uniqueness .
#Text=If your pet comes has an interesting background , consider it when picking a name .
#Text=Ask yourself :
#Text=Did my pet come from a unique or far-away location ?
#Text=Consider naming it after a city or country such as Cleveland or Italy .
#Text=Did my pet come from a specific family or shelter ?
#Text=Think about a name after the person you adopted your pet from , maybe like " Sherry " or " Lisa . "
#Text=If your vet has a unique name , such as " Mills , " perhaps consider that .
#Text=Did my pet come overcome a challenging situation .
#Text=Consider names to reflect that like : " Lucky " or " Chance . "
#Text=Choosing a Name Based On Personal Interest
#Text=Compare personal hobbies or games .
#Text=If you are a big fan of a specific hobby or game , think of a name that will reflect that .
#Text=This can be anything from sports teams to super heroes .
#Text=These names can be fun , unique , and show off your personality .
#Text=Names like this include something like : " Iron Man , " " Thor " , or " Loki " or " Brady , " " Lebron , " or " Sabathia . "
#Text=Review popular culture , actors and actresses , and/or cartoon characters .
#Text=Think about popular culture when picking a name .
#Text=You can pick something that reminds you of your pet ’s personality or appearance , or perhaps someone you look up , admire , or find amusing .
#Text=This may include something silly like : " The Doctor , " " Stimpy , " or " Dora . "
#Text=Investigate historical pets .
#Text=There are many famous pets from real-life situations , movies , or books .
#Text=Consider these classical or historical names when picking a name for your pet .
#Text=Famous dogs include " Checkers " ( Nixon 's dog ) and " Sunny " ( Obama 's dog ) .
#Text=Famous cats include Hemingway 's cat " Boise " and President Lincoln 's cat " Tabby . "
#Text=Pick a word from a language you do not speak .
#Text=If you think that a word is too boring sounding in your own language , consider using the same word but in a different language .
#Text=For example , the word “ white , ” in English translates to “ Blanco/a , ” “ Bianco/a ” in Italian , or “ Blanc ” in French .
#Text=Pick a name based on a pleasant sounding word .
#Text=You will be saying and writing your pet ’s name a lot .
#Text=You want to pick something that sounds pleasant to both your ears and your pet ’s .
#Text=Searching For Names
#Text=Read baby books .
#Text=These are great resources to get inspiration on a lot of different names .
#Text=You can even search by popularity and by gender .
#Text=Search online .
#Text=You can use popular search engines for popular pet names by breed , gender , age , country , or just about any specifications you can think of !
#Text=To get a better result in your search , try to be specific in what you ’re looking for .
#Text=Try things like :
#Text=Cat names with Greek origins .
#Text=Good names for Great Pyrenees puppies .
#Text=Hamster names for lazy hamsters .
#Text=“ Marvel superhero names good for pets .
#Text=Ask friends or family for suggestions .
#Text=A new pet is something to be excited about and news to share !
#Text=You can talk to those close to you for suggestions on naming your new family member .
#Text=Avoiding Specific Names
#Text=Avoid names that sound like commands .
#Text=You will be working with your pet to persuade good behaviors and dissuade bad ones .
#Text=You want to be as clear as possible when communicating with your pet .
#Text=If your pet ’s name sounds like a command , it may be confusing for the pet .
#Text=These might include names with a long o as it may sound like " No. "
#Text=Names like these include : Joe , Bo , etc.
#Text=Skip long or complicated names .
#Text=If you want your pet to recognize its name , it is best to stick to short names that are easy to pronounce .
#Text=You may want to avoid names like Mississippi , Sacramento , Fitzgerald .
#Text=If you like the sound of a long name , consider abbreviating it ( Missi , Mento , Fitz ) .
#Text=Stay away from inappropriate or rude names .
#Text=You will be using this name on documents .
#Text=You will be calling your pet this name in public and others will have to say it as well .
#Text=Stay away from offensive names and stick with something that can be heard or read by all .
#Text=Avoid names that include curse words or bodily functions .
#Text=Quick Summary
